# Urban Tree Canopy & Heat Vulnerability in Chicago

**Final Project — Earth & Environmental Science**  
**Midpoint First Idea**

---

## Project Overview

This project is dedicated to investigating the effect of urban tree canopy coverages on higher land surface temperatures and greater social vulnerability. This project will furthermore investigate the variation of urban tree canopy coverage in Chicago. It is clear that when it comes to urban heat islands, lower income communities and communities of colors are the ones that are affected the most. Trees can be considered the most effective mitigation stratehy due to their cost. The analysis will use spatial and demographic data that can be found publically.

---

## Research Question

**How does urban tree canopy coverage vary across Chicago neighborhoods, and are lower-canopy areas associated with higher land surface temperatures and greater social vulnerability?**

---

## Data Sources

Data set - Source - Spatial Coverage - Temporal Coverage - Variables - Format

#1 - Chicago Neighborhood Boundaries - Chicago Data Portal - Chicago, IL - NA - Neighborhood Name, Geometry - Shapefile
#2 - Chicago Tree Canopy Coverage - Chicago Data Portal - Chicago, IL - 2010 to 2020 - Percentage Canopy Coverage per Neighborhood - CSV/Shapefile
#3 - Landsat Land Surface Temperature - USGS Earth Explorer - Chicago Metropolitan Area - 2020 to 2020 - Land Surface Temperature in Degrees Celsius - GeoTIFF
#4 - NLCD Impervious Surface - USGS - National - 2021 - Percentage impervious surface - GeoTIFF
#5 - CDC Social Vulnerability Index - CDC ATSDR - Census Tract - 2020 - SVI Score, Income, Race/Ethnicity - CSV
#6 - American Community Survey (ACS) - tidycensus R package - Census Tract - 2020-2025 - Median Income percentage, POC, population - API via R


