##Project Overview

This project will dedicate to investigating how land cover in the Chicago area has changed between 2001 and 2020, and also to determining where urban expansion has ocurred at the expense of ecologically valuable land. This will occur through the analysis of two decades of data on land cover.

##Research Question
**How has land cover in Chicago changed between 2001 and 2021, where has urban expansion occured at the expense of forest, wetland, or agricultural land?**

##Data Sources
#1 - National Land Cover Database - USGS - Unites States - 2001,2011,2021 - Land Cover Class - GeoTIFF
#2 - NLCD Land Cover Change Product - USGS - United States - 2001-2021 - From/to class transitions - GeoTIFF
#3 - Chicago Metro Boundary - Chicago metropolitan agency for planning - 7-county Chicago Metro - Current - Regional Boundary - Shapefile
#4 - County boundaries - Tiger/Line Shapefiles - Cook, DuPage, Kane, Lake, McHenry, Will, Kendall - 2020, County Geometry - Shapefile

## Key Land Cover Classes

Class Value - Label - Ecological Significance

11 - Open Water - Aquatic Habitat
21-24 - Developed - Urban/Suburban Land
41-43 - Forest - Carbon Storage/Habitat
52 - Shrub/Scrub - Transitional Habitat
71 - Herbaceous Grassland - Native Prarie Remnants
81-82 - Pasture/Cultivated Crops - Agricultural Land
90 - Woody Wetlands - Flood Regulation/Habitat
95 - Emergent Herbaceous Wetlands - High Ecological Value

